#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:6
msgid "Summary"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:8
msgid ""
"This RFC proposes to expand, and make more explicit, Rust's governance "
"structure. It seeks to supplement today's core team with several _subteams_ "
"that are more narrowly focused on specific areas of interest."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:13
msgid ""
"_Thanks to Nick Cameron, Manish Goregaokar, Yehuda Katz, Niko Matsakis and "
"Dave Herman for many suggestions and discussions along the way._"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:16
msgid "Motivation"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:18
msgid ""
"Rust's governance has evolved over time, perhaps most dramatically with the "
"introduction of the RFC system -- which has itself been tweaked many times. "
"RFCs have been a major boon for improving design quality and fostering deep, "
"productive discussion. It's something we all take pride in."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:24
msgid "That said, as Rust has matured, a few growing pains have emerged."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:26
msgid ""
"We'll start with a brief review of today's governance and process, then "
"discuss what needs to be improved."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:29
msgid "Background: today's governance structure"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:31
msgid ""
"Rust is governed by a [core team](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust-wiki-"
"backup/blob/master/Note-core-team.md), which is ultimately responsible for "
"all decision-making in the project. Specifically, the core team:"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:36
msgid "Sets the overall direction and vision for the project;"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:37
msgid "Sets the priorities and release schedule;"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:38
msgid "Makes final decisions on RFCs."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:40
msgid ""
"The core team currently has 8 members, including some people working full-"
"time on Rust, some volunteers, and some production users."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:43
msgid ""
"Most technical decisions are decided through the [RFC process](https://"
"github.com/rust-lang/rfcs#what-the-process-is). RFCs are submitted for "
"essentially all changes to the language, most changes to the standard "
"library, and [a few other topics](https://github.com/rust-lang/rfcs#when-you-"
"need-to-follow-this-process). RFCs are either closed immediately (if they "
"are clearly not viable), or else assigned a _shepherd_ who is responsible "
"for keeping the discussion moving and ensuring all concerns are responded to."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:52
msgid ""
"The final decision to accept or reject an RFC is made by the core team. In "
"many cases this decision follows after many rounds of consensus-building "
"among all stakeholders for the RFC. In the end, though, most decisions are "
"about weighting various tradeoffs, and the job of the core team is to make "
"the final decision about such weightings in light of the overall direction "
"of the language."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:59
msgid "What needs improvement"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:61
msgid "At a high level, we need to improve:"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:63
msgid "Process scalability."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:64
msgid "Stakeholder involvement."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:65
msgid "Clarity/transparency."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:66
msgid "Moderation processes."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:68
msgid ""
"Below, each of these bullets is expanded into a more detailed analysis of "
"the problems. These are the problems this RFC is trying to solve. The "
"\"Detailed Design\" section then gives the actual proposal."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:72
msgid "Scalability: RFC process"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:74
msgid ""
"In some ways, the RFC process is a victim of its own success: as the volume "
"and depth of RFCs has increased, it's harder for the entire core team to "
"stay educated and involved in every RFC. The [shepherding process](https://"
"github.com/rust-lang/rfcs#the-role-of-the-shepherd) has helped make sure "
"that RFCs don't fall through the cracks, but even there it's been hard for "
"the relatively small number of shepherds to keep up (on top of the other "
"work that they do)."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:82
msgid ""
"Part of the problem, of course, is due to the current push toward 1.0, which "
"has both increased RFC volume and takes up a great deal of attention from "
"the core team. But after 1.0 is released, the community is likely to grow "
"significantly, and feature requests will only increase."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:88
msgid ""
"Growing the core team over time has helped, but there's a practical limit to "
"the number of people who are jointly making decisions and setting direction."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:92
msgid ""
"A distinct problem in the other direction has also emerged recently: we've "
"slowly been requiring RFCs for increasingly minor changes. While it's "
"important that user-facing changes and commitments be vetted, the process "
"has started to feel heavyweight (especially for newcomers), so a "
"recalibration may be in order."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:97
msgid "We need a way to scale up the RFC process that:"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:99
msgid ""
"Ensures each RFC is thoroughly reviewed by several people with interest and "
"expertise in the area, but with different perspectives and concerns."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:103
msgid ""
"Ensures each RFC continues moving through the pipeline at a reasonable pace."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:106
msgid ""
"Ensures that accepted RFCs are well-aligned with the values, goals, and "
"direction of the project, and with other RFCs (past, present, and future)."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:110
msgid ""
"Ensures that simple, uncontentious changes can be made quickly, without "
"undue process burden."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:113
msgid "Scalability: areas of focus"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:115
msgid ""
"In addition, there are increasingly areas of important work that are only "
"loosely connected with decisions in the core language or APIs: tooling, "
"documentation, infrastructure, for example. These areas all need leadership, "
"but it's not clear that they require the same degree of global coordination "
"that more \"core\" areas do."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:121
msgid ""
"These areas are only going to increase in number and importance, so we "
"should remove obstacles holding them back."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:124
msgid "Stakeholder involvement"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:126
msgid ""
"RFC shepherds are intended to reach out to \"stakeholders\" in an RFC, to "
"solicit their feedback. But that is different from the stakeholders having a "
"direct role in decision making."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:130
msgid ""
"To the extent practical, we should include a diverse range of perspectives "
"in both design and decision-making, and especially include people who are "
"most directly affected by decisions: users."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:134
msgid ""
"We have taken some steps in this direction by diversifying the core team "
"itself, but (1) members of the core team by definition need to take a "
"balanced, global view of things and (2) the core team should not grow too "
"large. So some other way of including more stakeholders in decisions would "
"be preferable."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:140
msgid "Clarity and transparency"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:142
msgid ""
"Despite many steps toward increasing the clarity and openness of Rust's "
"processes, there is still room for improvement:"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:145
msgid ""
"The priorities and values set by the core team are not always clearly "
"communicated today. This in turn can make the RFC process seem opaque, since "
"RFCs move along at different speeds (or are even closed as postponed) "
"according to these priorities."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:150
msgid ""
"At a large scale, there should be more systematic communication about high-"
"level priorities. It should be clear whether a given RFC topic would be "
"considered in the near term, long term, or never. Recent blog posts about "
"the 1.0 release and stabilization have made a big step in this direction. "
"After 1.0, as part of the regular release process, we'll want to find some "
"regular cadence for setting and communicating priorities."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:158
msgid ""
"At a smaller scale, it is still the case that RFCs fall through the cracks "
"or have unclear statuses (see Scalability problems above). Clearer, public "
"tracking of the RFC pipeline would be a significant improvement."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:163
msgid ""
"The decision-making process can still be opaque: it's not always clear to an "
"RFC author exactly when and how a decision on the RFC will be made, and how "
"best to work with the team for a favorable decision. We strive to make core "
"team meetings as _uninteresting_ as possible (that is, all interesting "
"debate should happen in public online communication), but there is still "
"room for being more explicit and public."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:171
msgid "Community norms and the Code of Conduct"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:173
msgid ""
"Rust's design process and community norms are closely intertwined. The RFC "
"process is a joint exploration of design space and tradeoffs, and requires "
"consensus-building. The process -- and the Rust community -- is at its best "
"when all participants recognize that"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:178
msgid ""
"... people have differences of opinion and that every design or "
"implementation choice carries a trade-off and numerous costs. There is "
"seldom a right answer."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:182
msgid ""
"This and other important values and norms are recorded in the [project code "
"of conduct (CoC)](http://www.rust-lang.org/conduct.html), which also "
"includes language about harassment and marginalized groups."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:186
msgid ""
"Rust's community has long upheld a high standard of conduct, and has earned "
"a reputation for doing so."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:189
msgid ""
"However, as the community grows, as people come and go, we must continually "
"work to maintain this standard. Usually, it suffices to lead by example, or "
"to gently explain the kind of mutual respect that Rust's community "
"practices. Sometimes, though, that's not enough, and explicit moderation is "
"needed."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:195
msgid ""
"One problem that has emerged with the CoC is the lack of clarity about the "
"mechanics of moderation:"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:198
msgid "Who is responsible for moderation?"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:199
msgid "What about conflicts of interest? Are decision-makers also moderators?"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:200
msgid "How are moderation decisions reached? When are they unilateral?"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:201
msgid "When does moderation begin, and how quickly should it occur?"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:202
msgid "Does moderation take into account past history?"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:203
msgid "What venues does moderation apply to?"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:205
msgid ""
"Answering these questions, and generally clarifying how the CoC is viewed "
"and enforced, is an important step toward scaling up the Rust community."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:208
msgid "Detailed design"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:210
msgid ""
"The basic idea is to supplement the core team with several \"subteams\". "
"Each subteam is focused on a specific area, e.g., language design or "
"libraries. Most of the RFC review process will take place within the "
"relevant subteam, scaling up our ability to make decisions while involving a "
"larger group of people in that process."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:216
msgid ""
"To ensure global coordination and a strong, coherent vision for the project "
"as a whole, **each subteam is led by a member of the core team**."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:219 src/1068-rust-governance.md:705
msgid "Subteams"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:221
msgid "**The primary roles of each subteam are**:"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:223
msgid ""
"Shepherding RFCs for the subteam area. As always, that means (1) ensuring "
"that stakeholders are aware of the RFC, (2) working to tease out various "
"design tradeoffs and alternatives, and (3) helping build consensus."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:227
msgid "Accepting or rejecting RFCs in the subteam area."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:229
msgid ""
"Setting policy on what changes in the subteam area require RFCs, and "
"reviewing direct PRs for changes that do not require an RFC."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:232
msgid ""
"Delegating _reviewer rights_ for the subteam area. The ability to `r+` is "
"not limited to team members, and in fact earning `r+` rights is a good "
"stepping stone toward team membership. Each team should set reviewing "
"policy, manage reviewing rights, and ensure that reviews take place in a "
"timely manner. (Thanks to Nick Cameron for this suggestion.)"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:238
msgid ""
"Subteams make it possible to involve a larger, more diverse group in the "
"decision-making process. In particular, **they should involve a mix of**:"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:241
msgid ""
"Rust project leadership, in the form of at least one core team member (the "
"leader of the subteam)."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:244
msgid ""
"Area experts: people who have a lot of interest and expertise in the subteam "
"area, but who may be far less engaged with other areas of the project."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:247
msgid ""
"Stakeholders: people who are strongly affected by decisions in the subteam "
"area, but who may not be experts in the design or implementation of that "
"area. _It is crucial that some people heavily using Rust for applications/"
"libraries have a seat at the table, to make sure we are actually addressing "
"real-world needs._"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:253
msgid ""
"Members should have demonstrated a good sense for design and dealing with "
"tradeoffs, an ability to work within a framework of consensus, and of course "
"sufficient knowledge about or experience with the subteam area. Leaders "
"should in addition have demonstrated exceptional communication, design, and "
"people skills. They must be able to work with a diverse group of people and "
"help lead it toward consensus and execution."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:260
msgid ""
"Each subteam is led by a member of the core team. **The leader is "
"responsible for**:"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:262
msgid "Setting up the subteam:"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:264
msgid ""
"Deciding on the initial membership of the subteam (in consultation with the "
"core team). Once the subteam is up and running."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:267
msgid ""
"Working with subteam members to determine and publish subteam policies and "
"mechanics, including the way that subteam members join or leave the team "
"(which should be based on subteam consensus)."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:271
msgid "Communicating core team vision downward to the subteam."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:273
msgid ""
"Alerting the core team to subteam RFCs that need global, cross-cutting "
"attention, and to RFCs that have entered the \"final comment period\" (see "
"below)."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:276
msgid ""
"Ensuring that RFCs and PRs are progressing at a reasonable rate, re-"
"assigning shepherds/reviewers as needed."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:279
msgid ""
"Making final decisions in cases of contentious RFCs that are unable to reach "
"consensus otherwise (should be rare)."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:282
msgid ""
"The way that subteams communicate internally and externally is left to each "
"subteam to decide, but:"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:285
msgid ""
"Technical discussion should take place as much as possible on public forums, "
"ideally on RFC/PR threads and tagged discuss posts."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:288
msgid ""
"Each subteam will have a dedicated [discuss forum](http://internals.rust-"
"lang.org/) tag."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:291
msgid ""
"Subteams should actively seek out discussion and input from stakeholders who "
"are not members of the team."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:294
msgid ""
"Subteams should have some kind of regular meeting or other way of making "
"decisions. The content of this meeting should be summarized with the "
"rationale for each decision -- and, as explained below, decisions should "
"generally be about weighting a set of already-known tradeoffs, not "
"discussing or discovering new rationale."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:300
msgid ""
"Subteams should regularly publish the status of RFCs, PRs, and other news "
"related to their area. Ideally, this would be done in part via a dashboard "
"like [the Homu queue](http://buildbot.rust-lang.org/homu/queue/rust)"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:304
msgid "Core team"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:306
msgid ""
"**The core team serves as leadership for the Rust project as a whole**. In "
"particular, it:"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:309
msgid ""
"**Sets the overall direction and vision for the project.** That means "
"setting the core values that are used when making decisions about technical "
"tradeoffs. It means steering the project toward specific use cases where "
"Rust can have a major impact. It means leading the discussion, and writing "
"RFCs for, _major_ initiatives in the project."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:315
msgid ""
"**Sets the priorities and release schedule.** Design bandwidth is limited, "
"and it's dangerous to try to grow the language too quickly; the core team "
"makes some difficult decisions about which areas to prioritize for new "
"design, based on the core values and target use cases."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:320
msgid ""
"**Focuses on broad, cross-cutting concerns.** The core team is specifically "
"designed to take a _global_ view of the project, to make sure the pieces are "
"fitting together in a coherent way."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:324
msgid ""
"**Spins up or shuts down subteams.** Over time, we may want to expand the "
"set of subteams, and it may make sense to have temporary \"strike teams\" "
"that focus on a particular, limited task."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:328
msgid ""
"**Decides whether/when to ungate a feature.** While the subteams make "
"decisions on RFCs, the core team is responsible for pulling the trigger that "
"moves a feature from nightly to stable. This provides an extra check that "
"features have adequately addressed cross-cutting concerns, that the "
"implementation quality is high enough, and that language/library commitments "
"are reasonable."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:335
msgid ""
"The core team should include both the subteam leaders, and, over time, a "
"diverse set of other stakeholders that are both actively involved in the "
"Rust community, and can speak to the needs of major Rust constituencies, to "
"ensure that the project is addressing real-world needs."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:340
msgid "Decision-making"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:342
msgid "Consensus"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:344
msgid ""
"Rust has long used a form of [consensus decision-making](http://en.wikipedia."
"org/wiki/Consensus_decision-making). In a nutshell the premise is that a "
"successful outcome is not where one side of a debate has \"won\", but rather "
"where concerns from _all_ sides have been addressed in some way. **This "
"emphatically does not entail design by committee, nor compromised design**. "
"Rather, it's a recognition that"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:350
msgid ""
"... every design or implementation choice carries a trade-off and numerous "
"costs. There is seldom a right answer."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:353
msgid ""
"Breakthrough designs sometimes end up changing the playing field by "
"eliminating tradeoffs altogether, but more often difficult decisions have to "
"be made. **The key is to have a clear vision and set of values and "
"priorities**, which is the core team's responsibility to set and "
"communicate, and the subteam's responsibility to act upon."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:359
msgid ""
"Whenever possible, we seek to reach consensus through discussion and design "
"revision. Concretely, the steps are:"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:362
msgid "Initial RFC proposed, with initial analysis of tradeoffs."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:363
msgid "Comments reveal additional drawbacks, problems, or tradeoffs."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:364
msgid "RFC revised to address comments, often by improving the design."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:365
msgid ""
"Repeat above until \"major objections\" are fully addressed, or it's clear "
"that there is a fundamental choice to be made."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:368
msgid ""
"Consensus is reached when most people are left with only \"minor\" "
"objections, i.e., while they might choose the tradeoffs slightly differently "
"they do not feel a strong need to _actively block_ the RFC from progressing."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:372
msgid ""
"One important question is: consensus among which people, exactly? Of course, "
"the broader the consensus, the better. But at the very least, **consensus "
"within the members of the subteam should be the norm for most decisions.** "
"If the core team has done its job of communicating the values and "
"priorities, it should be possible to fit the debate about the RFC into that "
"framework and reach a fairly clear outcome."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:381
msgid "Lack of consensus"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:383
msgid ""
"In some cases, though, consensus cannot be reached. These cases tend to "
"split into two very different camps:"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:386
msgid ""
"\"Trivial\" reasons, e.g., there is not widespread agreement about naming, "
"but there is consensus about the substance."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:389
msgid ""
"\"Deep\" reasons, e.g., the design fundamentally improves one set of "
"concerns at the expense of another, and people on both sides feel strongly "
"about it."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:392
msgid "In either case, an alternative form of decision-making is needed."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:394
msgid ""
"For the \"trivial\" case, usually either the RFC shepherd or subteam leader "
"will make an executive decision."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:397
msgid ""
"For the \"deep\" case, the subteam leader is empowered to make a final "
"decision, but should consult with the rest of the core team before doing so."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:400
msgid "How and when RFC decisions are made, and the \"final comment period\""
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:402
msgid ""
"Each RFC has a shepherd drawn from the relevant subteam. The shepherd is "
"responsible for driving the consensus process -- working with both the RFC "
"author and the broader community to dig out problems, alternatives, and "
"improved design, always working to reach broader consensus."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:407
msgid ""
"At some point, the RFC comments will reach a kind of \"steady state\", where "
"no new tradeoffs are being discovered, and either objections have been "
"addressed, or it's clear that the design has fundamental downsides that need "
"to be weighed."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:411
msgid ""
"At that point, the shepherd will announce that the RFC is in a \"final "
"comment period\" (which lasts for one week). This is a kind of \"last call\" "
"for strong objections to the RFC. **The announcement of the final comment "
"period for an RFC should be very visible**; it should be included in the "
"subteam's periodic communications."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:417
msgid ""
"Note that the final comment period is in part intended to help keep RFCs "
"moving. Historically, RFCs sometimes stall out at a point where discussion "
"has died down but a decision isn't needed urgently. In this proposed model, "
"the RFC author could ask the shepherd to move to the final comment period "
"(and hence toward a decision)."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:423
msgid ""
"After the final comment period, the subteam can make a decision on the RFC. "
"The role of the subteam at that point is _not_ to reveal any new technical "
"issues or arguments; if these come up during discussion, they should be "
"added as comments to the RFC, and it should undergo another final comment "
"period."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:428
msgid ""
"Instead, the subteam decision is based on **weighing the already-revealed "
"tradeoffs against the project's priorities and values** (which the core team "
"is responsible for setting, globally). In the end, these decisions are about "
"how to weight tradeoffs. The decision should be communicated in these terms, "
"pointing out the tradeoffs that were raised and explaining how they were "
"weighted, and **never introducing new arguments**."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:435
msgid "Keeping things lightweight"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:437
msgid ""
"In addition to the \"final comment period\" proposed above, this RFC "
"proposes some further adjustments to the RFC process to keep it lightweight."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:440
msgid ""
"A key observation is that, thanks to the stability system and nightly/stable "
"distinction, **it's easy to experiment with features without commitment**."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:443
msgid "Clarifying what needs an RFC"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:445
msgid ""
"Over time, we've been drifting toward requiring an RFC for essentially any "
"user-facing change, which sometimes means that very minor changes get stuck "
"awaiting an RFC decision. While subteams + final comment period should help "
"keep the pipeline flowing a bit better, it would also be good to allow "
"\"minor\" changes to go through without an RFC, provided there is sufficient "
"review in some other way. (And in the end, the core team ungates features, "
"which ensures at least a final review.)"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:453
msgid ""
"This RFC does not attempt to answer the question \"What needs an RFC\", "
"because that question will vary for each subteam. However, this RFC "
"stipulates that each subteam should set an explicit policy about:"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:457
msgid "What requires an RFC for the subteam's area, and"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:458
msgid "What the non-RFC review process is."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:460
msgid ""
"These guidelines should try to keep the process lightweight for minor "
"changes."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:462
msgid "Clarifying the \"finality\" of RFCs"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:464
msgid ""
"While RFCs are very important, they do not represent the final state of a "
"design. Often new issues or improvements arise during implementation, or "
"after gaining some experience with a feature. **The nightly/stable "
"distinction exists in part to allow for such design iteration.**"
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:469
msgid ""
"Thus RFCs do not need to be \"perfect\" before acceptance. If consensus is "
"reached on major points, the minor details can be left to implementation and "
"revision."
msgstr ""

#: src/1068-rust-governance.md:472
msgid ""
"Later, if an implementation differs from the RFC in _substantial_ ways, the "
"subteam should be alerted, and may ask for an explicit amendment RFC. "
"Otherwise, the changes should just be explained in the commit/PR."
msgstr ""

